exports[`cleaning pipeline — snapshot tests > snapshot: en-github-blog (en) 1`] = `
"
    <p>Today we are excited to announce GitHub Copilot Workspace, a new developer environment that reimagines how software is built from idea to implementation.</p>
    <p>Copilot Workspace starts with a natural language description of a task and builds a complete plan for implementing it. The developer can then review, modify, and execute the plan within the workspace.</p>
    <h2>From Issue to Pull Request</h2>
    <p>The typical workflow begins when a developer opens a GitHub issue. Copilot Workspace analyzes the issue description, the repository structure, and relevant code to propose a step-by-step implementation plan.</p>
    <p>Each step in the plan includes specific file modifications, new file creation, or deletion suggestions. The developer has full control to accept, reject, or modify any suggested change before it is applied.</p>
    <h2>Integrated Development Flow</h2>
    <p>What makes Copilot Workspace unique is its deep integration with the GitHub platform. Changes are automatically committed to a branch, CI/CD pipelines run against the proposed changes, and pull requests are created with full context.</p>
    <h2>Early Access</h2>
    <p>Copilot Workspace is now available in technical preview for GitHub Copilot Enterprise customers. We are collecting feedback to refine the experience before a broader launch later this year.</p>
  "
`;

exports[`cleaning pipeline — snapshot tests > snapshot: en-medium (en) 1`] = `
"
        <p>Rust has been gaining tremendous momentum in the systems programming world. For seven consecutive years, it has been voted the most loved programming language in Stack Overflow's developer survey.</p>

        <p>What makes Rust special is its ownership system. Unlike C and C++, Rust guarantees memory safety at compile time without needing a garbage collector. This eliminates entire classes of bugs including null pointer dereferences, buffer overflows, and data races.</p>

        <p>Like this article? Follow me for more content like this.</p>

        <h2>Memory Safety Without Garbage Collection</h2>
        <p>The borrow checker is Rust's most distinctive feature. It enforces strict rules about how references to data are created and used. At any given time, you can have either one mutable reference or any number of immutable references to a piece of data.</p>

        <pre><code>fn main() {
    let mut s = String::from("hello");
    let r1 = &amp;s;    // immutable borrow - ok
    let r2 = &amp;s;    // another immutable borrow - ok
    println!("{} and {}", r1, r2);
    // r1 and r2 are no longer used after this point
    let r3 = &amp;mut s; // mutable borrow - ok because r1, r2 are done
    println!("{}", r3);
}</code></pre>

        <h2>Fearless Concurrency</h2>
        <p>Rust's type system and ownership model make it possible to write concurrent code that is free from data races. The compiler catches potential race conditions at compile time, which is a game-changer for systems programming.</p>

        

        <h2>Industry Adoption</h2>
        <p>Major companies are adopting Rust for critical infrastructure. Microsoft is using Rust in Windows kernel components. Google has added Rust as a supported language for Android development. Amazon Web Services uses Rust for performance-critical services like Firecracker.</p>
      "
`;

exports[`cleaning pipeline — snapshot tests > snapshot: en-nbsp-comments (en) 1`] = `
"<article>
    
    

    
    
    

    <p>WebAssembly enables near-native performance in web browsers. It provides a compilation target for languages like C++, Rust, and Go.</p>

    
    

    <h2>Multi-language Support</h2>

    <p>WASM modules can be compiled from multiple languages, making it a versatile platform. Each language brings its own strengths to the web platform.</p>

    
    <pre><code>// Rust to WASM
#[wasm_bindgen]
pub fn add(a: i32, b: i32) -&gt; i32 {
    a&nbsp;+&nbsp;b
}</code></pre>
    

    
    <h2>Memory Model</h2>

    <p>The linear memory model provides sandboxed execution for WebAssembly modules. Memory is isolated from the host environment.</p>

    
    <table>
      <tbody><tr><th>Language</th><th>Relative Speed</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Native C++</td><td>1.0x</td></tr>
      <tr><td>WASM</td><td>1.1x</td></tr>
      <tr><td>JavaScript</td><td>3.5x</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>

    
  </article>"
`;

