exports[`cleaning pipeline — snapshot tests > snapshot: en-substack (en) 1`] = `
"
        <p>WebAssembly (Wasm) has evolved far beyond its original browser-based use case. In 2024, we are seeing Wasm being used in server-side computing, edge functions, plugin systems, and even blockchain smart contracts.</p>

        <h2>WASI: Beyond the Browser</h2>
        <p>The WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is perhaps the most exciting development in the Wasm ecosystem. WASI provides a standardized set of system calls that allow Wasm modules to interact with the operating system in a sandboxed manner.</p>

        

        <h2>Component Model</h2>
        <p>The Wasm Component Model introduces a way to compose Wasm modules together, enabling language-agnostic plugin systems. This is a major step forward for interoperability between different programming languages compiled to Wasm.</p>

        <p>Docker has integrated Wasm support, allowing developers to run Wasm containers alongside traditional Linux containers. This significantly reduces container startup times and memory footprint.</p>

        <h2>Performance Benchmarks</h2>
        <p>Recent benchmarks show that Wasm execution speed is within 10-20% of native code for most workloads. With ongoing improvements to the JIT compilation pipeline, this gap is expected to narrow further.</p>
      "
`;

exports[`cleaning pipeline — snapshot tests > snapshot: en-techblog (en) 1`] = `
"<article>
      
      

      
        <p>Microservices architecture has become the de facto standard for building large-scale distributed systems. Go, with its excellent concurrency support and small memory footprint, is an ideal choice for microservices.</p>

        <h2>Service Discovery</h2>
        <p>In a microservices architecture, service discovery is crucial. Services need to find and communicate with each other dynamically. Popular solutions include Consul, etcd, and Kubernetes service discovery.</p>

        <h2>Inter-Service Communication</h2>
        <p>gRPC is widely used for inter-service communication due to its efficiency and strong typing. Protocol Buffers provide a language-neutral way to define service interfaces.</p>

        <pre><code>func main() {
    srv := grpc.NewServer()
    pb.RegisterUserServiceServer(srv, &amp;userService{})
    srv.Serve(lis)
}</code></pre>

        <h2>Observability</h2>
        <p>Distributed tracing with OpenTelemetry, structured logging, and Prometheus metrics are essential for operating microservices in production. Without proper observability, debugging issues across services becomes extremely difficult.</p>
      
    </article>"
`;

